<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-178-390  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 178 390.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Simulation  March 1989 v52 n3 p95(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Qualitative methodology in simulation model engineering.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fishwick, Paul A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Qualitative methodology in simulation requires high level modelingconstructs such as causal graphs, bond graphs, or naturallanguage.andP;  Even though there exists a virtual continuum betweenqualitative and quantitative simulation methods, it is importantto discuss qualitative methods since they relate to notions ofprocess abstraction and discovery during model evolution.andP;  We willrefer to the evolutionary process as simulation model engineering.andO;We define the basic notions of qualitative simulation, givespecific examples for a pendulum system, and finally discussvarious issues and directions for future work.andP;  (Reprinted bypermission of the publisher.)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ModelingTechnologySimulation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartgraph.andO;Caption:   Object and action hierarchies. (chart)Pendulum bond graphs. (graph)Pendulum cellular automaton. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>